Formulated for Germany, but applicable elsewhere:

URL = http://okfn.org/wiki/PublicInterestInformationPolicyInGermany [http://blog.okfn.org/2009/02/17/public-interest-information-policy-in-germany/]


=Description=

"The [[Open Knowledge Foundation]]'s Jonathan Gray wrote a short piece for Berlin-based think
tank Das Progressive Zentrum on public interest information policy in
Germany. 

The piece finishes with three policy suggestions:

1. Support legislation as well as licensing and pricing policies that
support public re-usability of Public Sector Information. The creation
of a national register of PSI assets, and the commissioning of a
country-wide and cross-sector report would help to inform appropriate
activity in this area.
 
2. Support mandates for open access to publicly funded research.
These should target higher education institutions, as well as funding
bodies and umbrella organisations.
 
3. Keep the public domain in the public domain. Encourage publicly
funded cultural heritage institutions to allow digital copies of their
holdings to be re-used by the public. Encourage the adoption of
intellectual property law and policy that takes account of public
interest, as well as private interests"


